        {
            "id": "action",
            "instance": "fffdea43-9c41-422c-90a9-a9c9c6fa0b6e",
            "properties": [
                [
                    "name",
                    "Spearphishing Attachment"
                ],
                [
                    "ttp",
                    [
                        [
                            "tactic",
                            "TA0001"
                        ],
                        [
                            "technique",
                            "T1566.001"
                        ]
                    ]
                ],
                [
                    "description",
                    "RansomHub phishing emails deliver malicious file attachments — commonly macro-enabled Office documents, HTML smuggling payloads, or archive files containing executables — that drop or execute a loader when opened by the victim. Observed payloads in RansomHub campaigns include Cobalt Strike beacons, SystemBC, and commodity RATs that establish C2 connectivity and enable follow-on credential access. Attachment delivery bypasses link-filtering controls and provides direct code execution on the victim host, accelerating the timeline from initial access to lateral movement and ransomware staging. User execution (T1204.002) is relied upon to trigger the payload, often aided by social engineering content instructing the recipient to enable macros or extract and run the enclosed file."
                ],
                [
                    "confidence",
                    null
                ],
                [
                    "execution_start",
                    null
                ],
                [
                    "execution_end",
                    null
                ]
            ],
